---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Header from "../../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Booking to Boarding"
  description="A planning timeline for making travel feel smoother before you ever leave home."
>
  <Header />

<main>

  <section class="article-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">
        <a href="/elevate-your-travel/" style="color:inherit;text-decoration:none;">
          ← Elevate Your Travel
        </a>
      </p>
      <h1>Booking to Boarding</h1>
      <p class="article-hero__lead">
        A planning timeline for making travel feel smoother before you
        ever leave home.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="article-prose">
      <p>This page exists for two reasons. I got stranded in San Francisco because I failed to
      read the details of an Australian visa. And I got stuck inside the Louvre on my only sunny
      day in Paris because I overplanned. Through those experiences, I built a timeline that
      actually works.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="timeline">

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">Start Now</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Dream Destinations</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">You are not planning the trip yet. You are giving the trip a reason to exist.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>Before flights, hotels, or travel documents, decide where you actually want to go.
          Travel is about fulfilling something — whether that is a desire, a passion, or a curiosity.</p>
          <p>Whether it is the Super Bowl, Wimbledon, an exotic beach, or your favorite artist at
          Red Rocks — it is your list to create. Start simple. Expect it to grow.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="article-link" href="/elevate-your-travel/where-i-am-dreaming/">My Dream Destinations</a>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">As Early As Possible</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Visa &amp; Travel Requirements</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">Bad planning shows up at the airport.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>It is never too early to check travel requirements. A U.S. passport opens a lot of
          doors, but some countries still require visas, additional forms, vaccinations, or extra
          planning. Check entry requirements when you start considering a destination and again
          when you book the flight. The U.S. State Department is the best starting point.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">9 to 13 Months Out</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Flights</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">The dream list becomes useful the second a deal appears.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>Flight schedules usually open around 9 to 13 months out, depending on the airline.
          If you are using points, earlier is usually better, especially for partner redemptions.</p>
          <p>This is why having a dream list matters. When a good route or redemption appears,
          you can move quickly instead of starting from scratch.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">When You Book Flights</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Hotels &amp; Ticket Research</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">Flexibility is a feature, not a flaw.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>I usually book accommodation when I book flights, but I avoid prepaid rates unless
          I am completely locked in. Plans change. Trips evolve. Keeping hotel options flexible
          lets you adjust once the details become clearer.</p>
          <p>Also research ticket requirements for the sites you want to visit. Some sell out
          early or have specific purchase windows — the Last Supper always comes to mind. Knowing
          ahead of time saves you from missing out.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="article-link" href="/city-guides/">City Guides</a>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">2 Months Out</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Plans &amp; Ground Travel</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">You are not planning every minute. You are setting the trip up to work.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>This is when I start turning the idea of the trip into an actual plan. I do not need
          a minute-by-minute agenda, but I want a clear list of things to see, eat, photograph,
          and experience. Do not overplan. Some things are better left flexible for weather,
          energy, or mood.</p>
          <p>Once the plan starts to take shape, figure out ground transportation. Some cities
          need a rental car, others are better with public transit or rideshare. If you are
          renting in Europe and cannot drive manual, book an automatic early.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">1 Week Out</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Packing</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">Future you is not packing calmly at midnight.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>Open the weather app and start building the packing plan. Think through outfits,
          adapters, chargers, cameras, batteries, and any other essentials before the night
          before your flight. Do not wear the outfit you want pictures in at the Eiffel Tower
          to work — put it in your suitcase ahead of time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">3 Days Out</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Aircraft &amp; Flight Setup</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">Control what you can before the airport controls you.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>Check the aircraft and plan around it. One airline’s economy class can be completely
          different from another’s, and even the same airline can vary by route.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Can I charge my devices?</li>
            <li>Will WiFi work for the whole flight?</li>
            <li>Do I have lounge access?</li>
            <li>Is there food I actually want?</li>
            <li>Is there in-seat entertainment?</li>
            <li>What is my delay or cancellation backup plan?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-entry">
        <div class="timeline-entry__when">24 Hours Out</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__title">Final Adjustments</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__rule">At this point, you are not planning. You are executing.</div>
        <div class="timeline-entry__text">
          <p>Confirm reservations, check the weather, decide which days make sense for the items
          on your list, and make any final bookings. Decide what time you need to get to the
          airport. Schedule your transportation. Triple check your luggage.</p>
          <p>You have done the work. Now the goal is to leave calmly and enjoy the trip.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div><!-- end .timeline -->
  </div><!-- end .container -->

  <section class="dreaming-cta">
    <div class="container dreaming-cta__inner">
      <div>
        <h3>Plan early. Leave room to breathe.</h3>
        <p>Know what you want to experience, but leave enough room for the trip to become something memorable.</p>
      </div>
      <a class="button button--primary" href="/elevate-your-travel/">Back to Elevate Your Travel</a>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
